(11, 'RUET OJ Testing Contest 2', 'Alice And ChessBoard', 'Its Sunday afternoon, and Alice is in her room trying to figure out the rules of the game called Chess. She thinks shes almost got it, but shed like your help.\r\n\r\nAlice has placed a bishop on an empty chessboard. Given the position of the bishop and the positon of another square on the chessboard, Alice would like to know if the bishop can travel to that square in one move or not.\r\n\r\nChess is a game played on an 8*8 rectangular board. The rows of the board are numbered from 18 and similarly the columns are numbered from 18. (For this problem, you may assume that the rows are numbered from 1 to 8 from top to bottom and the columns are numbered from 1 to 8 from left to right). The bishop occupies a single square on the board (as does every other piece) and it can move any number of squares diagonally, but it cannot travel outside the board. Below is a picture demonstrating the moves of a bishop. The dotted squares are the squares the bishop can travel to in one move.\r\n\r\nlink\r\n\r\nInput\r\n\r\nIn the first line of input, there is a number T (1  T  200) denoting the number of test cases. Each of the next T lines contains the description of the T testcases. Each testcase contains four integers in a single line. The first two integer denotes the row and the column of the position of the bishop respectively and the second two integers denotes the row and the column of the postion of the targeted square respectively. It is guaranteed that the two squares wont be the same. And of course, each of these integers will be between 1 and 8.\r\n\r\nOutput\r\n\r\nFor each test case, print Yes (without the quote) in a single line if the bishop can travel to the targeted square in one move. Otherwise print No (without the quote) in a single line.\r\n\r\nSample\r\n\r\nInput	\r\n3\r\n5 6 5 1\r\n1 1 2 3\r\n3 4 5 2\r\n\r\nOutput\r\n\r\nNo\r\nNo\r\nYes', 'toph', '3\r\n5 6 5 1\r\n1 1 2 3\r\n3 4 5 2', 'No\r\nNo\r\nYes\r\n', 'No\nNo\nYes\n', 25),
(11, 'RUET OJ Testing Contest 2', 'Mind Reader', 'You: Guess an integer number, but dont tell me.\r\nYour friend: Okay!\r\n\r\nYou: Now multiply it by 3.\r\nYour friend: Okay.\r\n\r\nYou: Add 4 to it.\r\nYour friend: Done.\r\n\r\nYou: Multiply it by 4.\r\nYour friend: Wait okay, done.\r\n\r\nYou: Subtract 4 from it.\r\nYour friend: Okay!\r\n\r\nYou: Divide the number by 12. \r\nYour friend: Wait, how did you know that this number will be divisible by 12?\r\n\r\nYou: Ha Ha Ha! Magic my friend. Just do it please.\r\nYour friend: Okay, done.\r\n\r\nYou: What did you get?\r\nYour friend: 50.\r\n\r\nYou: You guessed 49, right?\r\nYour friend: Wow! You are a great magician!\r\n\r\nYou: Thanks. Its just some mathematical trick!\r\n\r\nAfter impressing your friend, you are thinking of creating a program to automate some process for yourself. The program should take a series of commands and the final number your friend got as input. You have to print the number your friend guessed. Simple and fun, right?\r\n\r\nInput\r\n\r\nIn the first line of input, there will be a number N (1  N  10) denoting the number of commands. In the next N lines there will be a command in each. The command will be any of the following 4 types:\r\n\r\nadd x\r\nsubtract x\r\nmultiply x\r\ndivide x\r\nWhere x is an integer. After that, in a new line there will be an integer that your friend got after all these operations. You can safely assume that after any operation, the number your friend got will be an integer and will not exceed 64-bit signed integer. You can also safely assume that your friend will always guess an integer initially.\r\n\r\nIn the input, there will be no command to multiply or divide by 0. And you can assume that all the commands are valid.\r\n\r\nOutput\r\n\r\nIn a single line, print the integer number your friend guessed.\r\n\r\nSample\r\n\r\nInput	                              Output\r\n5\r\nmultiply 3                      49\r\nadd 4\r\nmultiply 4\r\nsubtract 4\r\ndivide 12\r\n50	', 'toph', '6\r\nmultiply 3\r\nadd 4\r\nmultiply 4\r\nsubtract 4\r\ndivide 12\r\nadd 6\r\n19', '12\r\n', '12\n', 26),
(12, 'RUET OJ Testing Contest 3', 'CT Marks', 'In 5th semester  Of CSE  There Is a Course Named Software Engineering (SE). During 5th Semester of CSE 13 series Almost Every Student Got Excellent Marks In All Class Tests Of SE. There were  Total 4 Class Tests. As Our Both Class Representatives (CR) Are Too Much Lazy, Our Teacher Asked Them To Write A Program That Will Find Average Of Best 3 Class Test Marks Of All Students.\r\n\r\nInput\r\nInput starts with an integer T (= 125), denoting the number of test cases.\r\n\r\nEach case starts with a line containing  4 integer  denoting numbers of class tests.\r\n\r\nOutput\r\n\r\nOutput is  Average Of Best Three Class Test Marks. Average Number Has No Fraction Part. If There Is A Fraction Number Then Average Will Be The Next Number. Example: If Average Is 17.33 Then Average Will Be 18.\r\n\r\n\r\nSample Input\r\n\r\n2\r\n19 16 15 17\r\n20 16 18 17\r\n\r\nSample Output\r\n\r\n18\r\n19\r\n', 'shawon', '4\n17 17 15 19\n19 16 15 17\n20 20 20 20\n14 15 15 17', '18\r\n18\r\n20\r\n16\r\n', '18182016\n', 28),
(12, 'RUET OJ Testing Contest 3', 'Help Grameenphone', 'Recently a news has been published in a daily newspaper that GrameenPhone has almost reached to its limit of total number sim cards that they can sell using 017 series. In Bangladesh total digit of mobile phone number is 11 . So BTRC has allocated new 013 series for GrameenPhone. Now GrameenPhone has hired you as a programmer to write a program that will find total number of sim cards that they can sell with 013 series.\r\n\r\nInput\r\n\r\nInput contains a integer that is only 013\r\n\r\nOutput\r\n\r\nOutput is total number of sim cards that Grameenphone can sell with 013 series\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n. ', 'shawon', '013', '100000000\r\n', '', 29),
(12, 'RUET OJ Testing Contest 3', 'Searching For GF', 'Abu asif khan chowdhury is a very richman.But today asif is so sad because he has no girlfriend.So.he is thinking about what he should do.After thinking a while he discoveres a new idea.In the upcoming valentience day he will propose the girls who are still single by giving roses as a symbol of love.For this he goes to market and buy n roses.He wants to distribute roses among the maximum number of girls in such a way that each girls would get distinct positive integer number of roses.As he is busy with his work ,your task is to find the maximum number of girls he can give roses if he gives distinct number of roses to each girls.Among the girls who would get the maximum number of roses accept his propose and would become his girlfriend.You will also have to determine the maximum number of roses his girlfried can get from him.\n\nInput:\nIn the first line contains t (0<t<20),the number of test cases. the following t lines will contain the n(0<n<1001),the number of roses asif buys from the market.\n\nOutput: \n\nPrint the case number as shown in sample output,then print k,the maximum number of girls asif can give roses such that each one will get the distinct positive number of roses.Then print a space and print m ,maximum number of roses his girlfriend will get from him.Each output will seperated by a new line.\n\nsample input:\n3\n9\n5\n7\nsample output:\nCase 1:3 6\nCase 2:2 4\nCase 3:3 4\n\nN:B : In first test case asif can give roses maximum 3 girls. 3girls will get 1,2,6 roses respectively. So,maximum 6roses his GF will get from him. ', 'Nahid Al Asib', '4\r\n1000\r\n8\r\n1\r\n20', 'Case 1:44 54\r\nCase 2:3 5\r\nCase 3:1 1\r\nCase 4:5 10\r\n', 'Case 1:44 54\nCase 2:3 5\nCase 3:1 1\nCase 4:5 10\n', 30),
(12, 'RUET OJ Testing Contest 3', 'Problem of naughty boys ', 'Once there lived two very naughty boys named Uday and Tushar. But as we know birds of the same feather flock together, they were very good friends. There lived another boy named Asif in the village. One day Asif was coming from market after buying some food. On the way Uday and Tushar abducted him and beat him badly. They also took away all the foods from him. Among the items Asif bought, all of the items were in pair (i.e. 2 banana, 2 juices etc.) but there was only one bread. \nNow they want to divide the bread between them. But as we know they were not like typical naughty boys they wanted to divide the bread in such a way that the line along which the bread is divided maximizes the diving angle. They also want to know whether it is impossible to do such job. Can you help them? \nNote: The bread is in a size of parallelogram. \n\nInput: \nAt first there will be number of test cases T where 1<T<20. Then four points denoting the coordinates of the four points of the bread. The points will be in (x,y) format. Here, 0<x,y<10000.\n \nOutput: \nOutput the points along which the naughty boys need to divide the bread. Print 0 if there is no such way. \nThe output must be printed in the order as the input. \n\nSample input: \n1 \n1 1 \n3 1 \n4 3 \n2 3 \n\nSample output: \n3 1 \n2 3 ', 'Jubayer Hasan', '5\r\n1 1\r\n3 1\r\n4 1\r\n2 3\r\n\r\n1 1\r\n2 2\r\n2 1\r\n1 2\r\n\r\n3 3\r\n6 3\r\n3 4\r\n6 4\r\n\r\n3 3\r\n6 3\r\n4 5\r\n7 5\r\n\r\n4 1\r\n3 3\r\n9 1\r\n8 3\r\n\r\n', '3 1\r\n2 3\r\n0\r\n0\r\n6 3\r\n4 5\r\n4 1\r\n8 3\r\n', '3 1\n2 3\n0\n0\n0\n0\n', 31),
(12, 'RUET OJ Testing Contest 3', 'Big Prime Number', ' Peter wants to generate some prime numbers for his cryptosystem. Help him! Your task is to generate all prime numbers between two given numbers!\r\nInput\r\n\r\nThe input begins with the number t of test cases in a single line (t<=10). In each of the next t lines there are two numbers m and n (1 <= m <= n <= 1000000000, n-m<=100000) separated by a space.\r\nOutput\r\n\r\nFor every test case print all prime numbers p such that m <= p <= n, one number per line, test cases separated by an empty line.\r\nExample\r\n\r\nInput:\r\n2\r\n1 10\r\n3 5\r\n\r\nOutput:\r\n2\r\n3\r\n5\r\n7\r\n\r\n3\r\n5\r\n\r\nWarning: large Input/Output data, be careful with certain languages (though most should be OK if the algorithm is well designed)', 'spoj', '1\r\n100000500 100000600', '100000541\r\n100000543\r\n100000561\r\n100000567\r\n100000577\r\n', '', 32),
(13, 'C Programming Lab 1', 'Reverse String', 'Write a Program that take a string as input and print reverse of the string as Output.\r\n\r\n\r\nInput starts with test case t<=100.  Each test case has a string s.\r\n\r\n\r\nSample Input\r\n2\r\ncse\r\nand\r\n\r\nSample Output\r\nesc\r\ndna\r\n\r\n', 'Asha', '2\r\ncse\r\nand', 'esc\r\ndna\r\n', 'esc\ndna\n', 33),
(14, 'Object Oriented Programming Lab 1', 'Object Array', 'The Result of 5th semester need to be published as soon as possible but But there is a problem in Result making software. So RUET needs you to make a simple result making program.\r\n\r\nInput:\r\n\r\n5\r\nAshadullah 3.20\r\nAaashish 3.90\r\nAaabbas 3.80\r\nAaaanish 3.80\r\nShawon 3.16\r\n\r\nOutput:\r\n\r\n1.Aaashish\r\n2.Aaaanish\r\n2.Aaabbas\r\n3.Ashadullah\r\n4.Shawon', 'Asha', '5\r\nAshadullah 3.20\r\nAaashish 3.90\r\nAaabbas 3.80\r\nAaaanish 3.80\r\nShawon 3.16', '1.Aaashish\r\n2.Aaaanish\r\n2.Aaabbas\r\n3.Ashadullah\r\n4.Shawon\r\n', '', 36);
